# Mastering ArkType TypeScript: A Comprehensive Guide
created: 2025-07-03, last updated: 2025-09-12, [Read more](https://www.xjavascript.com/blog/arktype-typescript/)

ArkType provides a built - in mechanism for validating data against a schema.
You can use the
`validate` method to check if a given data object conforms to the schema:
```
const validationResult = userSchema.validate({
name: 'John Doe',
age: 30,
email: '[email protected]'
});
if (validationResult.success) {
console.log('Data is valid');
} else {
console.log('Data is invalid:', validationResult.problems);
```
...
To validate data against a schema, you simply call the
`validate` method on the schema object:
```
...
const productValidation = productSchema.validate(product);
if (productValidation.success) {
console.log('Product data is valid');
} else {
console.log('Product data is invalid:', productValidation.problems);
...
When validating data, it’s important to handle errors gracefully.
The
`validate` method returns an object with a
`success` boolean and a
`problems` array.
You can use this information to provide meaningful error messages to the user:
```
...
const result = testSchema.validate({ value: 10 });
expect(result.success).toBe(true);
});

